- [ ] Generates webp versions
- [ ] Generates responsive sizes
- [ ] Skips already-processed
- [ ] Dry-run mode works
- [ ] Reports progress and savings
- [ ] Tested on backup first

Apply depth-map parallax effect to ALL images site-wide using PixiJS displacement filters.

## ðŸ”§ Global Orchestration (REQUIRED)

All scroll animations MUST use the global Lenis + GSAP orchestration from `main.js`:

```javascript
const { lenis, ScrollTrigger, gsap } = window.ChrisTheme;
```

**DO NOT:** Create separate Lenis instances, import GSAP separately, or use raw RAF loops.
**DO:** Access everything via `window.ChrisTheme`, let main.js handle the RAF loop.

## Performance Strategy: Deferred PixiJS Loading

PixiJS is heavy (~200KB). Must NOT block initial page render.

### Load Order
1. **Critical path** (blocks render): HTML, CSS, fonts, hero image
2. **Deferred** (after DOMContentLoaded): Lenis, GSAP, main.js
3. **Lazy** (after first interaction or idle): PixiJS, depth-map system

### Implementation
```html
<!-- In default.hbs -->
<script>
  // Load PixiJS only after page is interactive
  if ('requestIdleCallback' in window) {
    requestIdleCallback(() => loadPixiJS());
  } else {
    setTimeout(loadPixiJS, 2000);
  }

  function loadPixiJS() {
    const script = document.createElement('script');
    script.src = '{{asset "js/vendor/pixi.min.js"}}';
    script.onload = () => window.ChrisTheme.initDepthMaps();
    document.body.appendChild(script);
  }
</script>
```

## Depth Map Generation

### Option A: Pre-generated depth maps (recommended)
- Generate depth maps at build time using Depth Anything V2
- Store alongside original: `image.jpg` â†’ `image_depth.png`
- Smaller runtime overhead, predictable quality

### Option B: Client-side depth estimation
- Use TensorFlow.js + MiDaS model
- More flexible but heavier (~50MB model)
- Only consider for dynamic/user-uploaded images

## Architecture

